  "articleSummary": "The article argues that “prompt injection” is the modern analogue of SQL injection: because large‑language‑model agents cannot reliably separate user data from executable instructions, an attacker can embed malicious commands in prompts, documents, or multimodal content to hijack the model’s behavior. It outlines three main attack vectors—direct injection, indirect injection via fetched content, and context hijacking—and shows how they can lead to tool misuse, data exfiltration, privilege escalation, and reputational damage. The piece is written as an analytical warning for developers and security engineers building LLM‑powered agents, using the classic SQL‑injection story as a metaphor, and it proposes a layered defense stack (input sanitization, injection classifiers, and least‑privilege tool design) rather than naïve “better prompts.”",
